                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/atoc-515" class="program-course-title">
              ATOC 515 Turbulence in Atmosphere and Oceans (3 credits)              <!---->            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-18530" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: Atmospheric &amp; Oceanic Sciences (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/615">Faculty of Science</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      Atmospheric &amp; Oceanic Sciences              : Application of statistical and semi-empirical methods to the study of geophysical turbulence. Reynolds' equations, dimensional analysis, and similarity. The surface and planetary boundary layers. Oceanic mixed layer. Theories of isotropic two- and three- dimensional turbulence: energy and enstrophy inertial ranges. Beta turbulence.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Winter 2015          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:                        David N Straub (Winter)                  </p>

    
          <ul class="catalog-notes">
              <li>Winter</li>
              <li>3 hours lecture</li>
              <li>Prerequisite (Undergraduate): MATH 314, MATH 315, a previous course in fluid dynamics (such as ATOC 512), or permission of instructor</li>
            </ul>
      </div>

